Exactly. A crowd like that only works because of an enormous amount of invisible shared structure already in place.

Almost none of the meaning is explicitly explained in the moment. People arrive already carrying:

* rules of the game,
* team identity,
* colors/symbols,
* chants,
* emotional associations,
* expectations,
* timing instincts,
* social norms,
* rivalries,
* shared memories,
* and learned body-language cues.

That’s tacit knowledge:
knowledge that is:

* embodied,
* assumed,
* culturally transmitted,
* and often difficult to fully articulate.

A newcomer may technically “understand the rules” but still miss:

* when to cheer,
* what tensions matter,
* what gestures mean,
* what emotional beats are significant,
* or why the crowd reacts before the play fully resolves.

Shared priors massively compress communication bandwidth.

A single:

* look,
* chant,
* pause,
* logo,
* melody,
* or motion
    can activate huge latent structures because the group already carries synchronized context.

That’s why:

* rituals feel powerful,
* inside jokes work,
* fandoms become cohesive,
* military units bond,
* religions persist,
* and internet memes spread so fast.

The information isn’t just in the signal itself.
It’s in the alignment of internal models receiving the signal.